[[File:Dorothy Parke.jpg|thumb|Dorothy Parke]]
'''Dorothy Parke''' (29 July 1904 – 5 February 1990) was a composer from [[Northern Ireland]], noted for children's works.
She was born in [[County Londonderry]], [[Ireland]], and studied piano with [[Ambrose Coviello]] and composition with [[Paul Corder]] at the [[Royal Academy of Music]] in [[London]] (LRAM, 1929). After completing her studies, she settled in [[Belfast]] and married Douglas Brown, a musician and teacher. Between 1930 and 1960 Parke taught music in Belfast and worked as a composer. Among her pupils were [[Norma Burrowes]] and [[Derek Bell (musician)|Derek Bell]]. {{See LMST|Dorothy|Parke}} She died in [[Portrush]], [[County Antrim]].<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IvoQQU1QL_QC&pg=PA362&dq=Dorothy+parke+grove&hl=en&ei=AtPxTJLXMMWt8Aapu7DRDA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CC0Q6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Norton/Grove dictionary of women composers|format=Digitized online by GoogleBooks|first=Julie Anne|last=Sadie|first2=Rhian|last2=Samuel|year=1994|accessdate=27 November 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cmc.ie/composers/composer.cfm?composerID=100|title=Dorothy Parke|accessdate=27 November 2010}}</ref>
==Works== Parke composed songs and piano solos, choral and vocal music. Selected works include:
*''St. Columba's Poem on Derry'', solo song *''A Song of Good Courage'', solo song *''The House and The Road'', solo song *''The Road to Ballydare'', solo song *''To The Sailors'', solo song *''Like A Snowy Field'' (1951) choral miniature *''Wynkyn, Blynkyn and Nod'' (1949) choral miniature<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.musicweb-international.com/classrev/2002/oct02/distaff.htm#ixzz16XrtafOr|accessdate=27 November 2010|title=THE DISTAFF SIDE: SOME IRISH WOMEN COMPOSERS}}</ref>
